  "text": "For completeness sake, even though we do not consider these here, we also mention that there are constructions that generalize the Rees algebra of an ideal in other directions, that is, not finding definitions that work for modules, but instead finds constructions over ideals with other properties than that of the Rees algebra. See for instance the quasi-symmetric algebra of an ideal defined in [CITATION_1] .",
